               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>The <title xml:lang="ta">Kācikāṇṭam</title>, <quote>The book of Kāci</quote>, that is <placeName xml:lang="sa">Kāśī</placeName> (Benares), is a Tamil version of the <term xml:lang="sa">Kāśīkhaṇḍa</term> of the late version of the Sanskrit <title xml:lang="sa">Skandapurāṇa</title>. The <title xml:lang="ta">Kācikāṇṭam</title> is the work of the <title xml:lang="ta">Teṉkāci</title> (<quote>Southern Kāśī</quote>) king <persName xml:lang="ta" role="author">Ativīrarāmapāṇṭiyaṉ</persName>, who ruled in the second half of the 16th century. See Raghavan (1960, p. 235). On <persName xml:lang="ta" role="author">Ativīrarāmapāṇṭiyaṉ</persName>, best known for his <title xml:lang="ta">Naiṭatam</title>, a Tamil version of the Sanskrit <title xml:lang="sa">Naiṣadha</title> by <persName xml:lang="sa">Harṣa</persName>, see Shulman (2012, pp. 155ff.).</p>
<p>The text is incomplete. See description below of U3 and mention of missing folios. It appears to be the collective work of several scribes, thus its inconsistent foliation.</p>
<p><emph rend="bold">Paratexts</emph>: marginal and in-text benedictions, title-page, invocation page, marginal chapter headers, in-text chapter completion statement, colophon, table of contents/total stanzas (U3, f295‒f297).</p>
<p>Description based on the examination of the original manuscript (January 2020).</p>
<p>Dimensions assessed at the time of examination.</p>      
                  </summary>
                  
